Dear Records Custodian,

Under the New York Freedom of Information Law (“FOIL”), N.Y. Public Officers Law §§ 84–90, I hereby request access to and copies of additional records held by the Town of Pine Plains, Dutchess County, relating to the authorization, execution, implementation, relocation, cancellation, and internal review of the Town’s proposed Flock Safety surveillance camera / automated license plate reader (“ALPR”) program.

This request is a follow-up to my prior FOIL request concerning Flock Safety surveillance cameras in Pine Plains, submitted through MuckRock: “FOIL Request: Flock Safety / surveillance cameras / Pine Plains” (Request No. 206780). This follow-up request seeks records not produced previously, including records clarifying contract authorization, signature authority, camera-site selection, relocation of the school-ground site, communications during gaps in the timeline, and records explaining the Town’s eventual decision not to proceed.

To the extent records have already been produced in response to the earlier request, I seek any additional, omitted, later-created, or previously withheld responsive records, as well as any records necessary to explain apparent gaps in the prior production.

This follow-up request is based in part on records already produced, which appear to show:

a Flock Safety contract or order form signed on behalf of the customer side by “Michael A. Beliveau, Sergeant,”
proposed camera placement including a location on school grounds,
later written approval to “move forward” with three camera locations,
and a later decision by Town officials not to proceed with the installation and to remove any work already done.

Timeframe: January 1, 2024 through the date this request is processed, and earlier records where necessary to identify the origin of the project, initial outreach, approval, procurement, or authorization.

Records Requested

For the purpose of this request, I seek all records, including but not limited to emails, attachments, memoranda, draft documents, text messages, meeting notes, calendar entries, approvals, legal reviews, procurement records, internal correspondence, handwritten notes, and electronically stored information, concerning the following:

Authority to Sign / Contract Authorization

All records reflecting who authorized, approved, reviewed, directed, or discussed execution of any Flock Safety contract, order form, pilot agreement, trial agreement, vendor agreement, memorandum of understanding, or related procurement document for Pine Plains.

This includes but is not limited to:

any delegation of authority authorizing Sgt. Michael A. Beliveau, or any other person, to sign on behalf of the Town or Pine Plains Police Department;
Town Board resolutions, motions, approvals, agenda items, or vote records relating to the agreement;
communications discussing whether the Town Supervisor, Town Board, Town Attorney, or any other official needed to approve the contract;
legal or internal review of signature authority;
records explaining why Sgt. Michael A. Beliveau appeared as the customer-side signatory on the Flock order form;
purchase approvals, routing sheets, or internal authorization records for the agreement.
Initial / Conditional Approval Records

All records referring or relating to any “conditional approval,” preliminary approval, informal approval, pilot approval, verbal authorization, or trial approval for a Flock Safety pilot, deployment, or proposed surveillance program.

This includes records identifying:

who granted any such approval;
when it was granted;
what conditions were attached;
whether the approval was given by the Town, the Police Department, or an individual official;
any communications referencing a trial or pilot being approved before formal contract execution.
Meeting Records and Missing Meeting Follow-Up

All records relating to any meetings, calls, conferences, or discussions concerning Flock Safety, ALPR cameras, surveillance cameras, or related procurement in Pine Plains, including but not limited to the December 2024 meeting(s) reflected in prior productions.

This includes:

meeting notes;
summaries;
minutes;
internal recaps;
handwritten notes;
calendar invitations and responses;
follow-up emails;
attendee lists;
call logs;
presentation materials;
action items arising from any meeting.
Camera Location Selection and School-Site Review

All records concerning the selection, recommendation, justification, evaluation, review, objection to, rejection of, or relocation of proposed camera sites, including any site on or near school grounds, residential areas, or privacy-sensitive areas.

This includes:

records explaining who selected each proposed site;
records discussing Stissing Mountain High School, Jackson Road, or school property;
communications with any school official, school district employee, or school representative;
revised maps, alternate site proposals, or replacement locations for any rejected site;
records referring to the “Condor” location being moved off school property;
site surveys, field notes, right-of-way review documents, and internal comments about residential or privacy-sensitive locations;
vendor recommendations concerning site placement;
internal Town or Police Department comments about privacy, visibility, or suitability of proposed sites.
Records Between Approval and Cancellation

All records from July 28, 2025 through February 4, 2026 concerning the Flock project, including but not limited to:

implementation planning;
permitting status;
installation scheduling;
vendor follow-ups;
project status updates;
internal concerns about cost, authority, procurement, privacy, school grounds, or public reaction;
communications about whether to continue, delay, revise, or stop the project.
Cancellation / Reversal Records

All records relating to the Town’s decision not to move forward with the Flock Safety installation and to stop or remove any work already done.

This includes:

who made the decision;
why the decision was made;
legal advice or internal concerns leading to cancellation;
communications with Flock Safety regarding termination, stop-work, removal, or shutdown;
records discussing whether any hardware had been installed, delivered, or staged;
records discussing whether the 60-day opt-out period had begun or expired;
records discussing financial consequences of cancellation or non-installation.
Financial, Procurement, and Payment Records

All records relating to the funding, budget impact, procurement handling, or financial review of the Flock agreement, including:

purchase requests;
requisitions;
purchase orders;
invoice records;
payment records;
budget approvals;
grant discussions or applications;
cost analyses;
records discussing the contract total, annual costs, cancellation terms, or automatic renewal terms;
records reflecting whether the contract was entered into through standard procurement procedures.
Data Sharing / Network Access / Privacy Review

All records concerning:

what outside agencies would have access to Pine Plains camera data;
whether Pine Plains would receive access to data from surrounding counties or agencies in New York, Connecticut, or Massachusetts;
any agreements, policies, or discussions regarding sharing, retention, audits, privacy, civil liberties, or acceptable use;
any internal concerns about surveillance near school grounds, residential areas, or village locations;
any training materials or policy documents concerning searches, hot lists, regional sharing, or data retention.
Communications of Specific Individuals

Please include records to, from, sent by, received by, or copying any of the following individuals or offices to the extent they were acting in an official capacity in relation to this matter:

Brian Walsh;
Michael A. Beliveau;
supervisor.secretary@pineplains-ny.gov
;
Town Board members;
Town Attorney or legal counsel;
Highway Department personnel;
Building Department personnel;
any Pine Plains Police Department personnel involved in the project;
Ashley Fernandez;
Erica Merten;
Erica Anderson;
Joe DiStefano;
Keegan McCready;
Emmie Smith;
Mark Smith;
any representative of Flock Safety or Flock Group, Inc.
Text Messages and Non-Email Communications

To the extent responsive records exist outside traditional email systems, please include:

text messages;
iMessages;
Signal messages;
WhatsApp messages;
Teams messages;
Slack or chat communications;
communications sent or received on personal devices if used for Town business;
handwritten or photographed notes concerning this matter.
Earlier or Omitted Records

If any responsive records were withheld, omitted, referred to another office, or not produced in response to the earlier request, please identify that fact and produce any now-available records or specify the office believed to maintain them.

If responsive records were not searched because they were believed to be held by the Police Department, Supervisor’s Office, Town Clerk, Highway Department, Building Department, or Town Attorney, please identify that office so that the request may be properly directed there as well.

Electronic Records and Metadata

For all responsive electronic records, I request production in native electronic format where possible, with all available metadata and email header information preserved.

This includes but is not limited to:

sender and recipient fields;
CC and BCC fields;
timestamps;
message IDs;
attachment metadata;
document creation and modification dates;
author fields;
file names and native file types.

Request for Segregable Non-Exempt Portions

If any responsive record or portion thereof is claimed to be exempt, please provide all reasonably segregable non-exempt portions and identify the specific statutory basis for each withholding or redaction.

If records are withheld in full, please provide an itemized description sufficient to identify the nature of each withheld record, including the date, sender/recipient, general subject matter, and the exemption claimed.

Preservation of Records

Please preserve all potentially responsive records, including emails, attachments, texts, chat messages, handwritten notes, and records stored on personal devices or non-Town systems if used for public business.

Fee Waiver Request

I request a fee waiver on the ground that disclosure of these records is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to public understanding of government surveillance, procurement, municipal contracting authority, and public accountability.

If fees are expected to exceed $200, please notify me before incurring them.

Public Availability of Communications

Please be advised that communications relating to this request, including incoming and outgoing correspondence, may be published on transparency platforms such as MuckRock.

Statutory Response Time

As required by N.Y. Public Officers Law § 89(3), I look forward to acknowledgment of this request within five business days.

Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter.

Sincerely,

Jordan Lassiter
Independent Investigative Journalist
